 ses pechiés une pecheresse royale”: Psalm Collects in an Early Fourteenth-Century Devotional Book -- tPART IV PERSUASIVE PERFORMANCES -- tDramatic Troubles of Ecclesia: Gendered Performances of the Divided Church -- tPreaching the Sins of the Ladies: Nicole Bozon’s “Char d’Orgueil” -- tMaking Names, Breaking Lives: Women and Injurious Language at the Court of Isabeau of Bavaria and Charles VI -- tPerforming the Nation: The Play Performed at the Great Feast in Christine de Pizan’s Biography of Charles V -- tPART V RE-ENACTMENTS AND LEGACIES -- tVariegated Performance of Aucassin et Nicolette -- tLate Medieval Representations of Storytelling and Story-Performance -- tParatextual Performances in the Early Parisian Book Trade: Antoine Vérard’s Edition of Boccaccio’s Nobles et cleres dames (1493) -- t“Resuscitating” Medieval Literature in New York and Paris: La femme que Nostre-Dame garda d’estre arse at Yvette Guilbert’s School of Theatre, 1919–24 -- tThe Pitfalls and Promise of Classroom Performance -- t« Dunc chante haut et cler » : remarques sur l’interprétation de la musique médiévale -- tTabula Gratulatoria0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA celebration of the groundbreaking achievements of Nancy Freeman Regalado in the field of medieval French literature.This collection of essays pays tribute to Nancy Freeman Regalado, a ground-breaking scholar in the field of medieval French literature whose research has always pushed beyond disciplinary boundaries. The articles in the volume reflect the depth and diversity of her scholarship, as well as her collaborations with literary critics, philologists, historians, art historians, musicologists, and vocalists - in France, England, and the United States. Inspired byher most recent work, these twenty-four essays are tied together by a single question, rich in ramifications: how does performance shape our understanding of medieval and pre-modern literature and culture, whether the nature of that performance is visual, linguistic, theatrical, musical, religious, didactic, socio-political, or editorial? The studies presented here invite us to look afresh at the interrelationship of audience, author, text, and artifact, to imagine new ways of conceptualizing the creation, transmission, and reception of medieval literature, music, and art. EGLAL DOSS-QUINBY is Professor of French at Smith College; ROBERTA L. KRUEGER is Professor of Frenchat Hamilton College; E. JANE BURNS is Professor of Women's Studies and Adjunct Professor of Comparative Literature at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill. Contributors: ANNE AZÉMA, RENATE BLUMENFELD-KOSINSKI, CYNTHIA J. BROWN, ELIZABETH A. R. BROWN, MATILDA TOMARYN BRUCKNER, E. JANE BURNS, ARDIS BUTTERFIELD, KIMBERLEE CAMPBELL, ROBERT L. A. CLARK, MARK CRUSE, KATHRYN A. DUYS, ELIZABETH EMERY, SYLVIA HUOT, MARILYN LAWRENCE, KATHLEEN A. LOYSEN, LAURIE POSTLEWATE, EDWARD H. ROESNER, SAMUEL N. ROSENBERG, LUCY FREEMAN SANDLER, PAMELA SHEINGORN, HELEN SOLTERER, JANE H. M. TAYLOR, EVELYN BIRGE VITZ, LORI J. WALTERS, AND MICHEL ZINK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aPerformance in literature. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAzéma, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirge Vitz, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlumenfeld-Kosinski, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Cynthia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Elizabeth A R, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Elizabeth A. R., econtributor.4ctb4https:/